\par Alex David Groce
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 
\par 
\par \tab \'93Fragments of a manuscript discovered after the storming of the \lquote Bastille.\rquote \'94  J. Storr.  Edited and abridged by A. Groce.  }{\i\f2 Historical Scholar}{\f2 , Aug. 810.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 NOTE:  These fragments are of dubious authenticity.  Stoddard and Glenn believe that they are apocryph
a dating from at least two generations after the Second Revolution.  Storr defends the pieced-together \'93document\'94 on the grounds that, whether it is an actual prisoner\rquote 
s record or not, it is relevant to understanding the conditions that led to revolution; 
however, as you will see, this is also open to debate.  Some would argue that the conditions the prisoner describes are for the most part universal throughout human experience; Storr has suggested that this is the true note of the manuscript\rquote 
s authenticity.
\par }\pard \qc \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 1:
\par \tab Dr. Johnson said \'93Sir, when a man knows he is to be hanged in a fortnight, it concentrates his mind wonderfully.\'94  This is so.
\par \tab \'93First,\'94 they say, \'93we will remove your eyeballs.  You must believe that this will be more painful than you can
 imagine.  Then, having blinded you, we will amputate your limbs, making sure to staunch the flow of blood; you see, we wish you to live some time.\'94
\par \tab At this point they always apply a burning iron to my back, and if I only knew what sign it was they brande
d me with I should be much better off.  The dream ends when I see the scalding tongs descending towards my eyes.  Sometimes the order is reversed and they amputate my arms and legs before blinding me.  This is excruciating, but bearable because I am aware
 it is only a premonition of what is to come.
\par \tab As I mentioned ear
lier, the warden denies all this.  He has just left, again.  There are two possibilities:  I am here because they want something from me (I have a secret, I have a secret) or because I want something from them (in which case I also have a secret, but they
 do not know it).
\par \tab The warden\rquote s story is highly unlikely.  That I would be so stupid as to assault an officer of the law is unbelievable.  If he insulted my woman (had I a woman) I would, perhaps, kill a member of the Securitet, but I would not get into a b
arroom brawl with him.  Therefore, if the story is true, then it means that I was seeking imprisonment.  Anyway, if a woman were so important to me I would remember her.
\par \tab The essential questions for you, my reader, are the same ones I ask myself:  who am I and what am I doing here?  And whose are the wings I hear beating in my dream?
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 NOTE:  The supposed original of the \'93first\'94
 fragment is written on a sheet of paper that dates to a period well before the revolution (c. 688) but the writing itself cannot, 
of course, be dated.  The numbering of the fragments is that assigned by Storr, since the sheets were not found together, nor were they numbered.  Because of the document\rquote 
s nature, the correctness of this order is uncertain, although in all fairness to Storr it must be admitted that his arrangement seems to be the most coherent.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 2:
\par \tab I will describe the wall of my cell.  It is gray, and it is stone.  That is the wall of my cell.
\par \tab I could dig my way out of the Chateau d\rquote If, but these walls are very solid and I do not have time.  The warden tells me that I am to be released in two days, which does not give me enough time to escape.
\par \tab }{\i\f2 She}{\f2  presents a problem.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 NOTE:  This is the first reference to a mysterious female figure later referred to as \'93the Lady.\'94  The identification of \'93}{\i\f2 she}{\f2 \'94 with \'93
the Lady\'94 has been generally accepted since 780, when Storr challenged Stoddard to a duel over the matter.  This fragment, curiously enough, was found on a piece of butcher\rquote s paper, soaked in blood.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 3:
\par \tab Th
e warden is a pleasant man, although he is too fat.  We play chess a great deal, and he always loses.  He says that I am more interesting than most of the other prisoners, who are (he claims, and I almost believe him) elderly political prisoners left over
 from the last regime, held only as a mercy\emdash 
many of them do not (again, this is what the warden claims) even remember why they are here.  They are pleasant, but usually somewhat distant, and many are afflicted with memory disorders, ranging from eidetic, bu
t obsessively trivial, memoriousness to complete amnesia (save for memory of certain abstract and incomprehensible political doctrines).  Only a few old firebrands still seem to harbor a grudge against the government, and they are in such poor health and 
of such great age that they are the most laughable of revolutionaries.
\par \tab It is the reactionaries, he tells me as he moves his knight to check my king, that are most useful to him, because they are often very good chess players.  But I am his only really worthy opponent.  \'93Mate in four,\'94
 I tell him as I take his knight.
\par \tab The dream is back again, after three years of sleepless nights.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 \tab NOTE:  After this point it will be necessary to present only certain, more interesting, fragments.  The bulk of the remaining
 two hundred are either written in what appears to be some form of code or indicative of such a disordered mental state that they are not easily parsed by the sane.  Four of the fragments are not available for study (see Storr, J., \'93
Academic Freedom and National Security\'94 in }{\i\f2 Historical Scholar}{\f2 , Jan. 789).
\par \tab The duration of the prisoner\rquote s stay in the \'93Bastille\'94 is a matter of considerable controversy.  Certain modern techniques of psychological treatment can produce a temporal disorientation similar to that a
pparently experienced by the prisoner.  Crantree suggests that a similar technique may have been employed by the pre-revolutionary government to rehabilitate prisoners.  The length of the final (and still incomplete) document suggests a period of at least
 five years, possibly more, unless the prisoner wrote at a truly astonishing rate.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 14:
\par \tab Fit the first.
\par \tab Should this record survive me, they may alter it.  Reader, beware!  In fact, the text you see may not be what I wrote, or, more importantly ma
y be a carefully selected and misleading portion of the whole.  The ravings of a madman are one thing, and these \'93notes from underwater\'94 as I should call them, are another.
\par \tab However, I believe that I have found a solution to this problem.  I have encrypted the whole within a portion\emdash 
the very part of this document that for their own devious purposes they will maintain unaltered is, in fact, a cryptogram that encapsulates the everything.
\par \tab I will not have time to complete my work, though, if they insist upon letting me go.
\par \tab She came again last night, after the dream of sweet torture.  She says much the same things as the warden, but more plausibly.  I cannot suspect her of being their agent.  She is of another order.
\par \tab \'93Sir,\'94 she says, \'93if you will look, your cell is not small and gray.  It is a fair-sized and hospitable room, only the door is locked from the outside.  It is much nicer than the warden\rquote s office.\'94
  She is (possibly) correct, but that does not fit my story very well.
\par \tab \'93Also, you have only been here for a week.  You punched an officer in a bar, and though you got the worst of the fight and he pled for clemency, you were sentenced to ten weeks.  The woman the officer insulted will be waiting for you outside.\'94

\par \tab This is also a plausible story.  In fact I am here to spy on the prison, and to ascertain that a certain man, X we shall call him, or \'93the prisoner of Zenda\'94
, the true King, is being held here.  The fight was a ruse, calculated to get me imprisoned.
\par \tab Only, the plan did not
 work quite right.  They somehow discovered my purpose, and have removed my memory of the rest of the plan, including who it is that I am a spy for.  It is even possible that I am in the service of another branch of the government, uncovering a plot from 
within by traitors to our country.
\par \tab She kisses my brow before she leaves.  There is nothing sexual about all of this, I assure you, despite her being young and darkly beautiful, and dressed in a diaphanous robe.  She is above my station, and I know it.  I h
ad sooner lust after an angel.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 
NOTE:  The original of this fragment contains, in addition to the uneven typescript here given, a series of illegible crayon scrawls.  Storr and other historians generally agree that the last of these marks can be read as saying:  \'93
Labyrinth is composed of crayons and overabundant Icons in constant delay (half-wife < forever). impermanent but what is beyond I ask?\'94  The various proposed interpretations of this remark are unsatisfying.  See the fragments numbered 103, 183, an
d 202 for my alternative reading.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 26:
\par \tab The warden informs me that I am to be hanged at dawn.  Apparently, the \'93officer\'94 suddenly took a turn for the worse, and is now dead.  I have killed a man.  It\rquote s actually very amusing, since I don\rquote t even remember him at all.

\par \tab My Lady says that this, too, is a ruse.  They are attempting to shock me out of my \'93mentally unbalanced\'94 state.  However, I have begun to suspect that I am not a spy, but that this \'93mental unbalance\'94 is a ruse on their part.  In fact.  
In fact.  Neither story is true\emdash neither mine nor theirs.  The real story is lost.
\par \tab In fact, a ruse on their part to convince me that I am mad, in the hopes that eventually my identity will completely break down and I will tell them whatever secret it is th
at I am supposed to have.  Standard tactics, to bewilder a poor man into surrendering his most guarded possession.  Whom the gods would interrogate, they first drive mad.
\par \tab It is true that this proposed hanging is also a ruse, although I wish it were not.  Execution might give me a bit of honor, because how can you take pride in going mad?
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 
NOTE:  Apparently the prisoner was correct.  The hanging is not mentioned again, and from time to time in the next hundred fragments he mentions new threats of execution
.  He does not take any of these very seriously, although later, once he has become even closer friends with the warden, he mentions how upset the warden seems whenever he has to carry these false messages (as below).
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 50:
\par \tab The warden has arrange
d for me to receive better food.  He often takes his own evening meal with me now.  Steak, crab, salmon, even corn and broccoli--the variety and quality is excellent.  I wonder why they allow him to lavish such special treatment upon me.  The warden himse
lf has given up all hope of me recovering my memory of the secret the government hopes to obtain.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 94:
\par \tab The warden today confessed.  He started to tell me that they were going to shoot me at midnight, but then stopped.  He sat down on the bed and said \'93It\rquote s a lie.  Don\rquote t tell them I told you, but you must have figured it out by now
\emdash you\rquote re not that crazy.\'94  I have come to trust the warden.  He likes me, and I like him.  I think in a sense we are the same kind of person, and perhaps serve similar fun
ctions within the apparatus of the state.  He shares my dangerous taste for Bach as well, and has always brought me whatever books I want, even some that are supposedly banned, such as the Barchester novels, although \'93banned\'94
 books have always been available to the intelligentsia.
\par \tab Not that I like him only because he performs certain useful services!  We talk a great deal now, although some of these conversations I have censored from this document because they are irrelevant to my purposes.  He tells me he 
is beginning work on a story about me.  A prison, I suppose, inspires men to write.  Boethius, Cervantes, Bunyan, etc.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 103:
\par \tab The warden showed me a picture of his daughter today.  It is strange to think that he has a life outside of this place.  At the end of the day he leaves the \'93Bastille\'94
 and walks through the back alleys to a tiny, dirty apartment in the Old Town.  He is as alone there as I am in my cell, and, ironically, does not even own a record player although he gave me one for Christmas
, (with some appropriate music, thus breaking two laws at once).  He is alone by choice--he sent little Eleanor abroad when the political situation became intolerable.  She is a small child, frail and birdlike, with a halo of fragile golden hair--complete
ly unlike her father in appearance.  Her mother died in the Fever of 610.  She must have been a beautiful woman.
\par \tab I wish he had left the picture with me.  I would place it on the mirror on my dresser.  Despite the rather posh furnishings, the gilt-framed bed, the ivory table, etc., this cell is barren.  It needs a child.
\par \tab The thought of poor Eleanor waving to her father from the ship makes me so sad, I wonder if I have a daughter, a wife, a family?  Perhaps these people, who I love though I do not remember t
hem, are part of the faceless crowd that I so despise.  Perhaps I look down on them from my barred window when the dull roar of their protest (or the sudden alarm and fight/flight when the Law disperses them) attracts my attention.  For all I know, I was 
once part of that anonymous and fickle mob myself.  In some little apartment in this city my wife may be saying even now, \'93We do not know where your father went.  God grant us that he will return home safely.\'94
  And my child is weeping for her father.
\par \tab 
But if I have a family, they are outside the labyrinth, I pray.  Inside, in here, and out there on the street, the walls shift constantly, walls made of the lies they tell me, the lies I tell them, the polite half-truths the warden and I exchange in order
 to avoid completely disheartening each other, the lies of the government and the revolutionaries and the masses.
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 My little girl, if she }{\i\f2 is}{\f2 , is not part of that.  My wife loves me, not some imagined secret I possess.  Even if my family is lost forever to me
, they are free and real.  All men, surely, are not wardens or prisoners?  Perhaps they are.  Is the nightingale that sings outside my window a part of the game--or does it have wings both real and metaphorical?  Hard to say.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 \tab One thing I am certain of:  the Lady is not a part of the labyrinth.  It could not contain her, though she lives within it.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 113:
\par \tab We witnessed an execution today, the first in months.  The Warden (Harding--he trusts me enough to tell me his name--I wish that I could return 
the favor), as is customary, did not appear before the public, but watched from inside.  My window provides an excellent view of the front yard.
\par \tab A large crowd was allowed inside the walls to watch the poor woman die.  The soldiers, in their brown dress uniforms, kept their rifles trained on the crowd, which ruined the effect of the military display.
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 Another group of soldiers, rifles properly shouldered, escorted the prisoner from the door.  They brought her to Mr. Guillotine.  It is interesting that (at le
ast as I saw it) only two of the hundreds of figures below were distinguishable, anything but faceless members of the mob or the rifle squad.  The central actor in the drama, of course, was the woman about to be executed.  She could not have been much old
e
r than twenty, and was breathtakingly beautiful.  She wore a pale sea-green dress, quite elegant, although not the present fashion.  Her hair was a smoldering red, and hung to her waist, unbound.  It was the brightest thing in the drab prison yard; in ear
ly winter the grass takes on a ghastly gray shade and the lonely tree is stark and barren.  She looked back and up at the Bastille for a moment, as if to greet the Warden and myself, or, more likely, to see her \'93home\'94
 for the last time.  Her face was pale and soft, already like an aging photograph--of a woman who was a beauty in her prime in the oldest living man\rquote s childhood, but, the old man sighs, \'93is now gone down to dust these forty years.\'94
  There was a dignity in her expression  and bearing that was almost unbearable to watch.
\par The other figure was Mr. Guillotine, the executioner.  He was dressed in white, from head to toe, even his boots, and wore the mask of a skull.  He was a head taller than any of the others gathered below, and his shoulders were mor
e than broad enough to match his height.  I wonder still how his identity was kept a secret; the mask hid his face, but surely he was recognizable in his outside life by his stature?  The only solution that I can offer is that he was a prisoner himself--p
erhaps with his death sentence altered to one of half-life, half-(acting as the agent of)-death.
\par Only two real people in the whole crowd, and one of them not a person but a thing, the face behind the mask of reality, the grinning skull always leering at you behind your back.  Death and the maiden.
\par She kneeled under the tree, and placed her head on the block.  A soldier stepped up and cut her hair.  It was a butchery, as savage as the execution in its own way.  When he was finished, her neck was bare.
\par The sho
uts of the crowd were becoming more bloodthirsty.  The Warden whispered to me that she was as unpopular with them as with the government; the reforms she had been foolish enough to suggest pleased neither the satisfied rich nor the rapacious poor.  It was
 not those reforms but the motivations behind them, he added, that had ensured her sentence.  The judge had explained the importance of maintaining the \'93sacred\'94 (how ironic) Separation.
\par Mr. Guillotine lifted the axe from beside the block and tested its edge
 against his gloved hand.  Satisfied, he raised it high in the air.  The girl on the block still said nothing, still refused to cry or scream, which angered the now roaring crowd.  As the mob drew closer to the tree the soldiers tightened their line.  The
 drum-roll ended and I turned away from the window.  I did not hear the axe fall, it is only a small sound, though sickening if you are close enough to hear it.  Only the cheers ensured me that justice had been done.
\par Perhaps she was my wife, and now I am a widower.  She was young enough to be my daughter.  God have mercy on our souls.
\par The warden told me this morning that the }{\i\f2 Institute de Physic}{\f2  announced today the discovery of a new particle.  The quantum of time, the chronon.  While we played darts, careful
 not to bury any of them in the finely paneled oak walls of the cell, he explained the significance of the discovery.  He thinks that I may have had a scientific career before my unfortunate loss of memory, and so is always telling me these things.
\par The chronon has both imaginary mass and charge (0+}{\i\f2 ei}{\f2  and 0-}{\i\f2 ei}{\f2 
, respectively), and that it is the fact that it has no anti-particle that provides time with a direction.  All physical processes would otherwise be symmetric, and past and present would be indistingui
shable.  It is only this mathematical quirk that makes yesterday more known but infinitely less reachable to us than tomorrow.  Below the unit of time marked by the quantity of the chronon, the arrow points both ways.
\par The physicists verified the existence of time by detecting the decay of a chronon.  The Warden offered an interesting suggestion.  \'93Since,\'94 he said, \'93
the chronon decays into something else that we have no name or theory for, but that is definitely not a temporal particle, and all chronons will
 eventually decay, although their half-life is provably unknowable, is it not the case that time has, in a sense, already come to a halt?  If it ever will, which it must, then it has already--only this is undetectable to our instruments.\'94
  Protons decay, so matter will eventually come to an end, but to imagine that time will also end, perhaps before that (in which case the protons will not decay, because there will be no time to measure half-lives by?) is strange.  
\par The girl is always on the block, the axe 
is always raised.  I am always a free man, and the warden is always smiling beatifically as his hypothesis is concluded and he buries his last dart in the bullseye.  We are all, always, about to die, are dying, are dead.  In fact, at every moment we are a
live, there are vast, unimaginable orders of magnitude more moments in which we are dead, \'93before\'94 and \'93after,\'94
 if those terms even apply (and so this is, like all tales told by men, a ghost story).  Our heads are always on the block, and thus, I suppose, by Johnson\rquote s dictum, our minds should always be clear.
