\par \tab The warden brushed his sausage-like fingers over the writing.  It was slightly raised from the wall, and seemed to vibrate at his touch.  He suspected that it had been embossed by machinery, but for what purpose he could not imagine.
\par \tab He turned aside and passed into the passage on the left.  A feather was lying on the ground, obviously pulled from the prisoner\rquote s pillow and left behind to taunt his pursuers.  \'93Be careful.  He\rquote 
s been here, and there will probably be a trap nearby.\'94
\par \tab They continued down the hallway.  A deep pit opened on their left, where the wall was broken and revealed a chamber with a large port
ion of its floor missing.  The warden peered over the edge, and saw a skeleton twenty feet below, the un-rotted clothing identifying it as one of the missing guards from his first excursion.
\par \tab The passage came to a dead end.  The warden retreated and took t
he other passage from the poetry room.  This passage was longer and fully intact.  Air vents on the ceiling blew chilled air down on them, and the warden shivered as the cold blasts played across the expanses of his flesh.  There was no door at the end of
 
this corridor, only an arch opening into a room almost as large as the chamber at the bottom of the Throat.  Where the vast spaces of that room had drifted into darkness, the surfaces of this room were nakedly exposed by a fierce light.  A sphere of unbea
rable brightness hung suspended from a cable in the center of the room, nearly blinding the group as they approached it along the refrigerated passage.
\par \tab As they entered the lit cavern, they heard a noise behind them.  They turned quickly, but only the warde
n, able to spin instantly on his invisible chair, caught a glimpse of the creature.  It was, he estimated, half the height of a man:  a thin ghost of ugly white flesh.  Its red eyes gleamed as they met his for the briefest of durations, and he thought he 
s
aw claws and fangs, but he was not really sure he had seen anything.  The form of the monster was taken directly from one of his recurring nightmares, the one in which wicked little white men with claws and fangs chased him among the labyrinthine stacks o
f the prison library.  The creature, if it had existed, had fled back into the poetry room.
\par \tab He decided not to pursue it.  He had not taken the long trip down the Throat in order to pursue phantasms through shadowy corridors.  He had taken it in order to pu
rsue the very real prisoner through those same shadowy corridors, and somehow his well-developed, if long dormant, skills told him that the prisoner had passed through the great chamber of light.
\par \tab He turned back.  \'93Did you see anything?\'94
\par \tab \'93No, sir.  We heard a noise, and turned, but there was nothing behind us.\'94
  He beckoned for them to follow him into the cavern.  Here the exits were clearly visible.  Twenty passages, counting the one at the head of which they stood, exited the circular room, evenly spaced along the walls.
\par \tab \'93Come on, we\rquote ll check them all.  He probably left a feather in front of one of them, and it\rquote s either a trap or the way he went--either way, it will tell us something.\'94  The guards followed without comment.
\par \tab The warden was correct.  The p
assage directly across the chamber from the one they had entered by was marked with a single feather.  The corridor was similar to the one they had entered by, a long steel hall of vent-chilled air blasts.  At the other end was a large and very dark room.
  Strange shapes loomed in the darkness and prevented the warden\rquote 
s light from revealing much more of the place than they could see directly in front of them.  The shapes appeared to be ruined machines and discarded storage containers.  The warden cautiously
 moved forwards.  Something about the place struck him as unbearably lonely, but in a triumphant rather than pathetic way:  here was a place which was proud of its desolation.  He moved over a small crab-like object, and it suddenly lit with a faint green
 glow and skittered away on its obscene insect-legs into the shadows, emitting a few mournful beeps.
\par \tab He followed it, passing over more pieces of discarded devices, none of which came to life.  He heard a sharp hiss of breath and started to turn, but was st
ruck by something before he saw more of what was behind him than a flash of white flesh.  Blackness took him, and he saw no more for some time.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 \tab When the warden awoke, he was no longer in the room of ruined parts.  He was lying on a street in a ruined ci
ty--miles, he imagined, below the tower.  Above him stretched abyssal darkness, a cavern far larger than anything he would have imagined was possible.  The only light was the pale blue luminosity of the ground.  He saw around him rows of dead houses and c
o
lumns of buildings that had been partly or completely reduced to rubble.  A moaning wind howled somewhere far away, though he could feel no movement in the air where he was.  In fact, the air was unnaturally still, as if it were weighted down and unable t
o
 move.  He sat up, and looked for his chair.  It and his light were gone, although his rations were untouched.  He stood up and brushed the dust off of his shirt.  The white dust stained his hands and he imagined that it gave his already pallid face a pos
itively ghastly appearance.
\par \tab The warden began to wander the streets.  He walked for hours without seeing anything other than ruined and abandoned dwellings and stores and offices.  He assumed they were dwellings and stores and offices--time had erased any d
ifferences between the buildings beyond size and architecture.  There were no wares in the stores, only dust.  A few of the buildings had pieces of metal in them that might have been parts of furniture, but nothing he could definitively establish as a bed
 or chair or desk.
\par \tab There was a shooting pain in his left side, but he ignored it, using the remnants of the stamina and stoic endurance he had once possessed.  Every ten or fifteen minutes he was forced to sit down and rest.  It was while he was resting th
at he saw another crab-like object on the floor of a particularly large building.  He kicked the thing, and it lit.  This time, instead of scurrying away, it circled around him rapidly, without beeping.  Then it started moving away from him, but slowly, a
n
d it paused whenever it was more than five feet away.  He staggered to his feet and followed, slowly, unsure what it might be or whether it might even somehow be a tool of the prisoner.  After a while it entered another building.  Inside this building he 
saw several crates, apparently untouched by whatever had ravaged the city.  He opened one, and inside was what he regarded as a gun.  He had never seen a real gun.
\par \tab He took it out and examined it.  He had seen many pictures of guns, and most of them looked 
dangerous.  This one looked deadly, and had obviously been designed by a master of psychology in order to convey instantly and very intensely the idea of threat.  The barrel was long and the six vibrating tubes underneath fed into a central bulb inside th
e electrical housing.  A \'93rifle,\'94
 he believed, was the proper terminology.  The rifle looked like something made for the highly specific purpose of killing things in an extremely unpleasant way.  He hefted it, feeling how light it was despite its impression of destructive weight.
\par \tab The crab creature had ceased to move.  He kicked it again, but it lay still and dark.  Apparently, its task completed, it had turned itself off.  Finally, he took the rifle and left, wondering why the crab creature had wanted to ar
m him.  He mentally shrugged.  Most of the world was incomprehensible.  To expect to be able to discern the motivations of tiny crab-like mechanisms scurrying through abandoned cities beneath ancient prisons was probably the height of hubris.
\par \tab He wandered 
a while longer, and grew hungry.  He sat down at the base of a broken statue, sweeping the shards of marble aside with his foot to make a resting place for his large fundament.  He pulled out his rations and again thanked God that whatever had attacked hi
m
 had not stolen his food as well as his light and chair.  He was just finishing the third of the bars when he saw a white figure moving through the shadows just beyond a pile of rubble.  He picked up the gun and carefully aimed it.  He drew in a deep brea
th and pulled the trigger.
\par \tab The black tip of the weapon glowed white for a brief instant, but nothing else happened.  A second later he noted that something else had actually happened, as the white figure toppled forwards and was hidden by the rubble.  The 
warden wondered if he had actually hurt it, or if it had seen the light of the gun and was pretending to be hit in order to lure him to it.  He was reasonably sure that if the creature wanted to catch him it would have no trouble doing so.  He had little 
to lose by going over to see what had happened to it.
\par \tab He stood, looked around, and then, having seen nothing moving, began to slowly walk towards the fallen monster.  He slowed to a halt at the edge of the rubble pile, then as swiftly as he could he rounde
d the corner and fired the gun.  Nothing happened.  The white thing was lying on the ground, face down, with no apparent wounds.  He kicked it.  Nothing happened.  He reached down and carefully touched it.  The white was in fact dust, and he was able to r
u
b some away.  The skin underneath was gray with specks of a sickening green, the same shade as the moss that lit the walls of the prison cells above.  He turned the creature over and saw his nightmare made flesh.  It did have wicked claws and red eyes and
 
sharp fangs.  It was only vaguely human, and in some way reminded him of a snake, although there was nothing really reptilian about it.  As he brushed the dust from its chest, he discovered something disturbing and inexplicable.  A number was written on i
ts chest, dyed in black ink.  }{\b\f2 #600033001005}{\f2 , the tattoo read.  The number, of course, was of the same form as a citizen\rquote s identification number, but obviously this thing was not a citizen of the Hierarchy.
\par \tab He examined the creature closely, but found nothin
g else of note.  Eventually, exhausted by his efforts, he crawled into a hole in a concrete barrier and went to sleep.  He slept fitfully, and dreamed that the prisoner and the angel were interrogating the gray and green creature in a huge torture chamber
,
 one such as the old warden had told him was hidden somewhere down here in the depths and had been used in the days when the Hierarchy had been somewhat less morally sound.  The angel and the prisoner kept asking the creature one question, again and again
, relentlessly beating and burning and cutting and strangling it, killing it a thousand times over.  }{\i\f2 \'93What is a man?  What is a man?  The heavens declare that you must answer, what is man?\'94}{\f2 
\par \tab He woke up unrested but unable to resume his sleep.  He wandered for four more days in this manner, traveling randomly and sleeping fitfully, slowly exhausting his rations and noticing the pain in his left side increase.
\par \tab Finally, he rounded a crest and saw before him a gathering of twenty of the white-dust coated monste
rs, and in the center of the group, tied to a pole, the prisoner.  He fired the rifle at the beasts, but before he could kill more than three of them they overwhelmed him. One of them sank its fangs into his arm and he lost consciousness.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 \tab When he awoke he was at the bottom of the Throat.  He saw a hideously fat man lying on the ground a few feet away.  The man\rquote 
s white silk shirt was ripped and soiled, and his bloated flesh escaped its confines and glistened wetly in the light.  His left arm was torn, still bleeding, and his badge of office was broken in half.
\par \tab The warden realized with a sudden certainty that the man was himself.  He looked at his own body.  He was a thin, angular man, not quite six feet tall, with a two great cloth-covered bundles bound i
n chains on his back.  He wore the gray uniform of a prisoner, although it was covered in fine white dust.  There was a bite on his right arm, where his sleeve was torn, but it didn\rquote 
t hurt.  A number, he knew, was tattooed across his chest in black ink:  }{\b\f2 #122142001122}{\f2 
.  He climbed the stairs and brought down some of the guards, telling them a half-truth:  that their warden was at the bottom of the stairs, but that he had suffered a terrible blow to his head and might be delirious.  They did not trust him an
d bound his hands before they allowed him to lead them down, but they did follow him back to the bottom of the Throat.
\par \tab The prisoner woke when the guards injected him with the needle one of them brought.  He looked at his former warden and appeared to grasp the situation with an instant and perfect awareness.  The prisoner smiled and spoke.  \'93
Guards, this is the man I was seeking.  Take him upstairs.  I will deal with him after I have washed.  No.  First, bring me a chair.\'94  
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 The guards brought the new warden a chair and then carried the former warden to what had been the prisoner\rquote s cell.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 \tab They released 
him the next day, after breaking the bonds that had been placed on his wings and presenting him with his pardon and his payment.  The new warden apologized to him for the Hierarchy\rquote 
s error, and then they opened the front gate and he stepped out and walked 
for fifteen minutes down the dirt path without looking back.  Then he turned back to face the mighty tower, and laughed the beautiful, deep, loud, honest laugh of a good man.  He spread his wings and flew towards the rising sun.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 THE END
