\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 179:
\par \tab Ce
rtainly an implausible tale.  I am not fond of the scientific romance, if that is what it is.  But I cannot tell the warden that I have figured out what it means.  How trivial!  I already knew that he loved parts of his job, and hated others (mostly the t
orture, and the paperwork).  Meanings are always banal when they are expressible in words.
\par \tab It would devastate him if I were not to praise it.  He is, really, a very insecure man.  His obesity bothers him, and he is ashamed of his political leanings.
\par \tab The Lady came last night, but only looked at me sternly.  \'93Madness,\'94 she said, \'93is one thing.  But to intentionally delude oneself is a dangerous game.  It is not a game, at all.\'94
  I pleaded and she finally relented (only after I reminded her of the dismemberment I had just suffered) and kissed my brow.  That kiss is a better weapon than a sword, I think.  \'93You will come to your senses in time,\'94 she said.  Then she added, 
\'93I hope so, at least, which is something.\'94
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 183:
\par \tab Shots were fired today in the s
treets, after dark.  I could see nothing.  The Warden knows nothing; they have decided that in order to prevent panic, information about the situation is to be restricted to those who already know it and those who are not interested in it.  He is afraid h
e was followed to his apartment last night.
\par \tab A speculation (jocular):  perhaps there is a quantum particle of identity, let us call it the \'93I\'94on; let us further suppose that mine have all but a few decayed, but these few they cannot detect; I cannot detect 
them either, but they remain, so I am constant, despite erasure.  When I talk to the warden, we exchange \'93I\'94
ons, in minute numbers, not enough to change who we are, but enough to be convinced that we both exist.  This is all there is to communication.  The only question, then, worth asking, is whether eventually all \'93I\'94
ons decay or whether there is anything that persists.  Perhaps once the chronons are gone, the \'93I\'94ons remain?
\par \tab The Lady appeared this morning, after long absence, and my heart was filled with fire.  She did not stay long, and spoke in riddles again.  She said, \'93\lquote Now,\rquote  said she, \lquote 
I know the cause, or chief cause, of your sickness.  You have forgotten what you are.\rquote   Also said to a prisoner, in one of the books you have here on your shelf.\'94  She
 pointed to the well-stocked shelf--I possess a number of books that would get the Warden in trouble if it were known he had provided them to me.  \'93
But you are close to remembering.  And I will protect you if you ask, though your understanding is but poor.\'94
\par \tab I asked her, \'93So I will remember who I am soon?\'94
\par \tab \'93Not in the sense that you mean; that is almost irrelevant.  But yes, you already have remembered, but not yet.\'94
