\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 190:
\par \tab A mutation, unexpected, of my nightly torments.  Again the hot searing of
 my flesh, my back marked, the symphonic pain as they scrape the flesh from my hands and feet with rough stones.  But I am doubly present in this version of the dream; not only the object of the torture, but an indifferent observer, watching from above.  
M
y point of view is fractured, and although I can still feel the excruciations, they are somehow abstract and removed.  I watch the proceedings first from the ceiling, then I descend and borrow the eyes of Mr. Guillotine, who was not present a moment befor
e.  Through the skull-mask (if it is a mask and not merely an inversion of the usual pattern of flesh on bone) I clinically note the precision with which he uses his scalpel.  
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 The end of the dream:  I notice that my features have been distorted by the pain
, at first into a caricature, red and ugly, with trickles of bright blood flowing from my scalp, but then transformed into something beautiful, the face of the Warden, then that of his daughter, and finally the woman with the lovely red hair.  They turn 
\'93me\'94 over, but the dream always (I experienced this variation three times now) ends before I can see the image on my back.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 193:
\par \tab On reflection, I have been too harsh in judging the warden\rquote s story.  Although, perhaps to give my criticism would be k
inder than to tell him the truth--that whatever its merits, he can never publish the story.  I am curious as to why he, in an offhand manner, uses the few words and phrases that the government has determined upset the people and distract them from more re
levant issues.  Of course, perhaps he is of my mind on those questions, as I have suspected from time to time.
\par \tab What upset me at first was the obvious element of wish-fulfillment in the story.  How can he imagine that my position is any better than his?  At
 least he can with some confidence state his own name.  But after much thought I have concluded that although he is wrong--my position is not preferable to his--I am also wrong to imagine that his position is preferable to mine.  He is a good man, though,
 and supposes that he alone is guilty.  He does not suspect that I am no easier in my conscience than he is.  In this one thing we differ.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 196:
\par \tab A nightmare, different.  At my window, the fanged and clawed devil of the warden\rquote s story.  The image was lifelike, and the creature\rquote 
s face my own, distorted by time and subterranean life.  For a moment, I was disoriented and imagined that I was hanging from the bars looking in on the creature, asleep in my bed.
\par \tab Perhaps not a nightmare.  I am very frightened, and wish it were morning.
\par \tab Much later, this same night.  I finally managed to resume my slumber, briefly, and I believe I have \'93solved\'94 my usual dream.  Instead of patiently watching the torture, this time I grabbed Mr. Guillotine\rquote 
s arm, whether to stop him or to guide his incisions I do not know.  He and the others, the things I will not describe, vanished.  I turned myself over, and saw the symbol on my back, the perpendicular burns, and knew that I would live, (at least in the d
ream).
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 FRAGMENT 202:
\par \tab This is the end.  The shouting in the streets has prevented me from sleeping of late.  It is like the first years of my imprisonment come again.  My beard has grown long and I have grown accustomed to the luxury of my cell.  But it w
ill all end tomorrow.  I am not to be hung--though, to be sure, it would concentrate my mind to know how I will meet Death.  In what guise, other than the freedom that approaches even now, will that specter haunt me?  The Lady assures me that all will be 
well (all manner of thing shall be).  \'93You must have hope, even if your only son is about to be killed, hope no matter what.\'94
\par \tab I am not so sure, but have some hope (I cannot disobey her completely).  The warden is more worried.  Last night he showed me my f
ile.  I finally realize the nature of the secret that they hoped to persuade me to deliver into their hands.  However, they do not know, even now, that I never had that secret.  No, that is not correct.  I do have the secret, but they have it too, only th
e
y have buried it so well they have forgotten it.  I would say that they are right, that such a Thing does make people unsettled, unhappy and unquiet, but they seem to be pretty unsettled and unhappy and loud anyway, so maybe that is not exactly it.  Perha
ps they know this, and have only buried the truth so that it can show off by returning again after a time, as if from the dead, \'93come back to tell you all,\'94
 and thus attract our attention, even our awe.  It has pulled that trick before, but it is something worth seeing for yourself I imagine.
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 
The warden says that we must be sure, if we both make it out alive (perhaps I will die tomorrow, which would be a relief, because I somewhat expect it), to find each other when things settle down.  He has friends among 
the revolutionaries, and I may receive some compensation as a victim of the current government.  
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 \tab I will not allow compensation; I am not innocent.  My file shows that I did strike the officer, although my own injuries were much worse than his.  The sente
nce was light, despite the fact that they had been looking for some excuse, any excuse, to put me away.  To discover my secret!  It is no wonder they haven\rquote t managed to deal with the present unrest.
\par \tab All of the tricks, and ruses, and the construction of so many layers of the labyrinth and to what end?  Something else entirely, a page from the real story.  I could tell them this, but only the warden would not believe I was mad.
\par \tab I would have been released a long time ago if I had not been annually deemed \'93mentally unfit for release.\'94
  Fortunately, my mission has been successful.  The King is not a prisoner here now, but has visited certain prisoners from time to time.  There is some evidence, of a convincing nature, that he was once imprisoned in this very ce
ll, even died here (but he has visited me since then).  I am honored; or perhaps, He is insulted.  I will report all of this to my superiors, if I can figure out who they are, but they may be too busy saving their skins from the mob to care.  Maybe I will
 just report it to anyone I can find, to my imagined family or to Eleanor if I find passage over the sea with her father.  The Lady already knows, of course--she is the King\rquote s mother, or his bride.
\par \tab I wonder if she is the woman whom the officer insulted, th
e woman I defended, in fact, or the poor woman with hair of fire.  Perhaps it is as in that book by Chesterton, and this is an asylum, not a prison, and all who have heard of my mad attack on a person of the state have been imprisoned here as well.  It do
es not matter.
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 The B-Minor Mass (another gift from the warden, delivered this morning) has reached the }{\i\f2 Agnus Dei}{\f2 , the agony of God.  }{\i\f2 Dona nobis pacem}{\f2 
.  God grant us. . .  Grant you, reader, a similar situation, perhaps.}{\i\f2 
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 \tab I hear the crowd rising now, a wave 
bearing everything away before it.  Chaos come again is never a lovely thing to behold, even when it is just, which is only somewhat the case now.
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 The walls are coming down, perhaps even the walls of the labyrinth itself.  But this also means that the grou
nd is falling away, and I am about to fly, whether I am ready or not.  I must put away my pen and await the opening of the cell door.
\par }\pard \qc \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f2 #
